          "body": "Psalm 115:4-8 contains one of the Old Testament's most sustained and devastating critiques of idol-worship, paralleled in Isaiah 44:9-20 and Jeremiah 10:3-5. The psalm's rhetoric is a systematic inventory of every sensory organ — mouth, eyes, ears, nose, hands, feet, throat — paired with the same negation: 'but they cannot.' The inventory is not accidental; it catalogues exactly the capacities that a living, responding, personally present God would exercise. Yahweh speaks (He gave the Torah); He sees (Psalm 34:15); He hears (Psalm 34:17); He smells the fragrance of acceptable worship; He acts with His hand (Psalm 98:1); He moves in salvation. The idol has the anatomy of a god without the life. The section's most theologically potent claim is verse 8: 'Those who make them will become like them, everyone who trusts in them.' Idol-worship is not merely futile; it is transformative in the worst possible direction. You become what you worship. The idol is mute, blind, deaf, inert — and so does the idolater become, in spiritual terms: unable to hear God, unable to see His works, unable to speak His praise. This principle has been developed with precision by modern scholars like G. K. Beale (*We Become What We Worship*, 2008) and reaches its New Testament expression in Romans 1:21-23, where those who exchange the truth of God for images become futile in their thinking and darkened in heart."
