          "title": "Mortality and the urgency of praise — from this time forth and forever",
          "body": "The psalm's final movement (115:16-18) provides both a cosmological grounding and a doxological urgency. Verse 16 situates the community within the created order: the heavens belong to Yahweh; the earth has been given to humanity. This is not a statement of divine absence from earth but of delegated stewardship — the earth is humanity's realm of responsibility, and praise of the God who made it is a primary human task. Verse 17 introduces the psalm's sharpest urgency: 'The dead do not praise the LORD, nor do any who go down into silence.' This is not a statement of eschatological despair — it reflects the Old Testament's consistent emphasis that the present life is the arena of doxology. Sheol offers no praise; the assembly in which the living gather does. The implication is direct: if you will praise God, you must do it now, while you are alive, in the gathered community. Verse 18 draws the conclusion with the psalm's most expansive time-marker: 'we will bless the LORD *from this time forth and forever*.' The mortality named in verse 17 becomes the motive, not the obstacle: precisely because death is real and near, present praise becomes urgent and endless in intention. The psalm that opened with a plea for God's glory (115:1) closes with a community committed to delivering that glory without end."
