        "title": "Glory belongs to the name — the crisis of divine honor in a world of taunts",
        "range": "115:1-3",
        "excerpt": "Not to us, O Lord, not to us, but to Your name give glory because of Your lovingkindness, because of Your truth.",
        "body": "The psalm opens not with a lament but with a doxological vow — a pre-emptive redirection of all potential honor away from Israel and toward the divine name. The doubled 'Not to us' (115:1) is one of the Psalter's most deliberate rhetorical constructions. It anticipates the question the nations have already asked (115:2) and answers it before it is finished: whatever God does or does not do in response to Israel's circumstances, the glory cannot land on Israel. The two grounds named — *chesed* and *emet* — are the paired covenant attributes of Yahweh announced at Sinai (Exodus 34:6) and form the theological bedrock of Israel's confidence. He is worth glorifying not because of Israel's record but because of His own unbroken covenant character.\n\nThe nations' taunt in verse 2 ('Where, now, is their God?') is a theological challenge, not merely a military insult. In the ancient Near Eastern world, the defeat or apparent abandonment of a nation implied the defeat or absence of its deity. If Yahweh does not visibly intervene, the conclusion the nations draw is that He is either absent, weak, or fictional. The psalmist refuses every option. Verse 3 delivers the counter-claim in two clauses: God is in the heavens, and He does whatever He pleases. The first clause answers the 'where' question — He is not absent; He is transcendent. The second clause answers the implied 'why' — He is not weak; He is sovereign. His freedom of will (*kol-asher chaphets asah*, 'whatever He pleases He does') places Him entirely beyond the categories that govern idol-worship: idols do what their makers make them do; Yahweh does what Yahweh delights to do.\n\nThis opening movement is the entire psalm in miniature. The taunt that generates the crisis (115:2), the sovereignty that answers it (115:3), and the covenant attributes that ground confidence (115:1) — all three movements of the psalm's body (idol-polemic, call to trust, blessing-oracle) are implicit here. Calvin rightly observes in his *Commentary on the Psalms* that the psalmist's renunciation of self-glory is not false humility but theological realism: when the living God is the actor, any honor that lands on the creature is misplaced.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chesed* (lovingkindness, 115:1) is covenant loyalty — the disposition of a suzerain who keeps faith with his vassal beyond the terms strictly required. *Emet* (faithfulness, 115:1) is reliability, moral consistency, the correspondence between promise and performance. Together they appear in Exodus 34:6 as the defining attributes of Yahweh's name — making 115:1 a conscious echo of the Sinai self-revelation. *Chaphets* (pleases, 115:3) — to take delight in, to desire; God's will and God's delight are not in tension."
